{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_dungenesscrab_ver01/data/sn84020662/00414185435/1957112701/0323.xml":{"full_text":"Judge Denies\nPostponement\nOf Beck Trial\nSEATTLE iffi\u2014King County Su\nperior Judge -Malcolm Douglas\nyesterday denied a motion by the\nattorney for Dave Beck Sr. that\nthe grand larceny trial of the\nInternational Teamsters Union\npresident be postponed.\nIt is scheduled to start Monday.\nThe attorney, Charles S. Bur\ndell, based his motion on his con\ntention that adverse publicity\nwould make it difficult for Beck\nto get a fair trial at this time.\nBurdell also said Beck is due\nin Washington, D.C., Monday as a\nwitness in a civil suit involving\nthe eligibility of James Hoffa to\nsucceed Beck as president of the\nteamsters union.\nIn. denying the motion, Judge j\nDouglas said a civil case should\nnot take presidence over a crim\ninal case and .that Dec. 2 was\nsuggested by Burdell as the start\ning date for Beck\u2019s trial when\nBurdell received a previous delay.\nBeck is charged with misap\npropriating the proceeds form the\nsale of a union-owned automobile.\nHis son, Dave Jr., was convict\ned Saturday on two counts of\ngrand larceny involving the sale\nof two other union-owned cars.\nAllies Urge NATO\nMeeting Despite\nPresident\u2019s Illness\nPARIS, UR\u2014Britain, France,\nWest Germany and Italy urged\ntoday that the scheduled NATO\nsummit conference take place\nnext month despite President Ei\nsenhower\u2019s illness, with Vice Pres\nident Nixon taking the Chief Ex\necutive\u2019s place.\nThese countries\u2014chief Euro\nf pean members of the North At\nlantic Treaty Organization\u2014made\ntheir views known in answer to\nqueries from the U.S. delegation\nto NATO here. Similar views\nwere expressed by the Nether\nlands and Turkey. Greece sug\ngested a postponement.\nThe United States officially of\nfered earlier today to send Nixon,\nif this was agreeable to the other\nmembers of the alliance.\nInformed sources in London\nsaid the British government feels\nthe conference should go on as\nscheduled with Nixon as the top\nU.S. representative. They said the\nBritish view was that the meeting\nstill should be held at the heads j\nof government level and that j\nthere should be no postponement.\nSimilar reactions were ex\npressed by France, Italy and The\nNetherlands.\nJupiter Rocket 'Falls Short in Test\nMISSILE TEST CENTER, Cape'*:\n\u25a0Canaveral, Fla., UP>\u2014The Army\nfired its big Jupiter rocket last I\nnight, but the 1,500-mile range]\nmissile failed to complete its\nplanned flight.\nMoments after the 70-foot in\ntermediate-range ballistic missile\nblazed into the tropic sky at 9:10\np.m. EST, the Army issued a\nstatement that said it failed to\ncomplete its programmed flight\nbecause of technical difficulties.\nSix congressmen watched the\nfiring.\nTo hundreds of spectators\nwatching along the beach on this\nisland midway along the Florida\neast coast, the Jupiter was a spec\ntacular sight as it rose from a\nbillow of smoke and flame on the\nlaunching pad.\n\u2022It appeared to travel straight\nup, trailing a yellow flame. Then\nit became a purplish light high in\nthe sky. It was visible for about\nfour minutes and was brighter\nthan any star.\nThe Defense Department state\nment said: \u201cThis t^st of the Ju\npiter, under development by the\nArmy, is one of a series of inter\nrriediate range and intercontinen\ntal ballistic missile flight tests\nconducted at the Cape Canaveral\nrange.\u201d\nA Free and Abundant America Will Give Thanks\n(By The Associated Press)\nAmericans prepared today to\n\u2022give thanks for another year\u2019s\nharvest of freedom and abun\ndance, but the shadow of Presi\ndent Eisenhower\u2019s illness dark\nened somewhat the usual joyful\nspirit of the time.\nPrayers for the President\u2019s swift\nand complete recovery will be\nsaid tomorrow in many morning\nreligious services which have\nbfsen an integral part of thanks\ngiving ever since the Pilgrims\nfirst celebrated it. Otherwise, re\nports from across the country in\ndicated that Americans will fol\nlow'the patterns set in past years.\nThey will' rush from city to\ncountry, from country to city, and\nfrom village to village, jamming\ntrains, planes, buses and private\ncars to join friends and relatives\nfor the day. Some will make it a\nfour-day weekend.\nOne of the most unusual church\nservices tomorrow will be held in\nthe DeWitt Church, in an unheat\ned, as yet unfurnished building of\nthe Bernard Baruch Housing Proj\nect in Manhattan\u2019s lower East\nSide. Non-denominational services\nwill be held in English, Spanish\nand Russian at the church, the\nfirst built inside a public housing\nproject in the city.\nMerchants\u2019 parades for chil\ndren, featuring fancy floats and\ngiant balloons in fantastic shapes,\nwill be another Thanksgiving Day\nfeature. The biggest of the par\nades, Macy\u2019s in New York, will\nbe held in the morning.\nIt will strike a timely note with\none of its huge balloons. To the\nmore conventional figures of the\nturkey and the toy soldier, the\nparade this year is adding a new\nballoon\u2014a \u201cSPACEMAN\u201d.\nFootball games will add their\ncolor, noise and enthusiasm to the\natmosphere in all parts of the\ncountry. There are nine major\ncollege tilts and numerous lesser\nones, not to mention a flock of\nhigh school engagements.\n_:_i\nNo Freight Rate Action\nBy Maritime Board\nUntil Friday at Earliest\nWASHINGTON UP)\u2014Indications\nare that the Maritime Board won\u2019t\nact before Friday, at the earliest,\non freight rate increases proposed\nby two shipping lines serving\nAlaska.\nThe increase, asked by Alaska\nSteamship Co. and Coastwise\nLines, will go into effect at 12:01\na.m. Monday unless suspended by\nthe board.\nSeveral courses of action are\nopen to the board. It may (1) find\nthe rates reasonable and permit\nthem to go into effect; (2) permit\nthe increase to become effective\nsubject to refund if later disal\nlowed; (3) suspend the increase\nfor up to four months subject to\nfurther investigation and hearing,\nor (4) permit part of the increase\nto become effective and suspend\nthe remainder.\nRequests for suspension of the\nproposed increase pending a hear\ning have been received from the\nTerritory of Alaska, the Depart\nment of Interior, the General Ser\nvices Administration and various\nStates-Alaska shippers.\nPRESIDENT RESTS AFTER SLIGHT\nSTROKE; SIGNS 12 DOCUMENTS\n-<3\nBankrupt Phone\nCo. Will Try\nTo Reorganize\nSEATTLE, WV-The Seward,\nHaines, Petersburg and Wrangell'\nproperties of the bankrupt Alaska\nTelephone Corp. have been taken\noff the market and efforts are be\ning made to reorganize the com\npany, court officials disclosed.\nVan C. Griffin, referee in bank\nruptcy for the U.S. district court,\nsaid today a hearing had been\nscheduled Jan. 27 before Federal\nJudge William J. Lindberg for\npresentation of the reorganization\nplan if it is ready.\nThe reorganization plan must\nhave the approval of the Securi\nties and Exchange Commission,\nthe referee, trustee and judge,\nand then be submitted to the\ncreditors whose claims outstand\ning against the corporation total\nbetween $800,000 and .$1,000,000.\nOne of the key features of the\nreorganization, said a trustee\u2019s\nattorney, is prompt conversion of\nthe Seward telephone system\nfrom manual to dial operations.\u201d\nThere are about 700 telephones\nin the Seward system and another\n700 at Haines, Wrangell and Pe\ntersburg.\nSpokesmen said the reorgani\nzation plan was being worked out\nin the hope that creditors would\nrealize a greater amount on their\nclaims, and improved, continued\nservice could be maintained at\nthe four remaining communities\nin the system.\nN.Y. Stock Market\nRebounds Vigorously\n(By The Associated Press)\nThe New York Stock Market\nrebounded vigorously after the\nheavy sell-off that greeted the\nannouncement of the nature of\nPresident Eisenhower's illness\nyesterday.\nKey issues opened up 1 to 4\npoints.\nLabor Secretary Mitchell\nGives Chins-Up Speech\n(By The Associated Press)\nSecretary of Labor James P.\nMitchell, giving the gist of a\nchins-up speech by Eisenhower\nscheduled for Cleveland last night\nand cancelled by the President\u2019s\nillness, urged the nation to accept\nthe \u201causterity and privations\u201d re\nquired to give aid to the free\nworld.\nMitchell spoke in New York\nlast night.\nWASHINGTON, UP)\u2014The White\nHouse announced today President\nEisenhower on his own motion\nsigned some government docu\nments and initialed others.\nPresidential Press Secretary\nJames C. Hagerty said the ailing\nEisenhower met for a half hour\nin his bedroom with Gen. Andrei\nJ. Goodpaster, White House staff\nsecretary.\nEisenhower is under treat\nment for what his physicians\ndescribe as an occlusion or\nNixon Praises\nMrs. Eisenhower\u2019s\nCourageous Action\nWASHINGTON, UP)\u2014For the\nthird time in 26 months, Mrs.\nDwight D. Eisenhower is watch\ning over a sick husband.\nVice President Nixon described\nas \u201ccourageous\u201d her action Mon\nday night in attending a state din\nner for King Mohammed V of\nMorocco, after President Eisen\nhower had suffered a mild stroke.\nBut last night, Mrs. Eisenhower\njoined the ailing President in din\ning from trays and watching tele\nvision for a couple of hours in\ntheir White House living quarters.\nIn advance of the Monday night\ndinner, the White House had an\nnounced only that Eisenhower\nhad suffered \u201ca chill.\u201d\nNixon, who escorted the First\nLady to the dinner and sat by\nher, commented:\n\u201cI might say that Mrs. Eisen-1\nhower\u2019s performance last (Mon\nday) night, knowing what she\nknew, was as courageous as I\nhave ever seen by anyone. It was\nperhaps the most difficult time\nshe has ever had.\u201d\nNo state functions interfered\nduring Eisenhower\u2019s previous ill\nnesses\u2014a heart attack in Denver\nin September 1955 and an ileitis\noperation in June 1956. In each\ncase, Mrs. Eisenhower took a\nroom in the hospital to be near\nthe President, and remained with\nhim thru convalescence.\nUnited Thanksgiving Day Service\nASSEMBLY OF GOD CHURCH\nThursday, November 28, 1957 10:00 A.M.\nConducted through the efforts of the Nome Ministerial Assn.\nPrelude Miss Harriet Brown\nDoxology.Congregation\nWord of Welcome Miss Harriet Brown\nGreetings and Invocation Thomas A. Knudson\nCongregational Songs Roald Amundsen\n\u201cBlessed Assurance\u201d No. 221\n\u201cPraise Him\u201d No. 86\nChoral Group Assembly of God\n\u201cCount Your Many Blessings\u201d\nAnnouncements Thomas A. Knudson\nSolo.Mrs. Edgar Bibb\n\u201cWhat Ood Has Done\u201d\nScripture Lesson Willard Mecklenburg\nChoral Group The Covenant Church\n\u201cWhy Should I Be Anxious?\u201d\nMessage Everett Bachelder\n\u201cThe Works of Thy Hands\u201d\nCongregational Hymn\n\u201cOh, For a Thousand Tongues to Sing\u201d No. 44\nBenediction.Edgar Bibb\nblockage in a brain artery. The\npopular term for that it a slight\nstroke.\nHagerty said Eisenhower talked\nto Goodpaster about \u201csome pend\ning government business\u201d as well\nas signing 12 papers and initial\ning a 13th.\nEarlier, the President\u2019s doctor,\nMaj. Gen. Howard M. Snyder, re\nported Eisenhower slept well and\n\u201cawoke refreshed.\u201d\nA brief medical bulletin said\nEisenhower \u201ctook His usual sh6w\ner and shave and just had a nor\nmal breakfSst.\u201d t\nHagerty described the <\u00a3hlef\nExecutive as being in \"fink\"\nspirits, and amused by a con\ntinuing \"slight difficulty\" in\npronouncing hard words, a. re\nsuit of his illness.\nAt his news conference later,\nHagerty said he could add noth\ning to what the doctors have re\nported. about prospects for Eisen\nhower\u2019s complete recovery wi&in\na \u201creasonable\u201d time.\nIn a question-and-answer ses\nsion with reporters, however,\nHagerty appeared to reopen the\ndoor a crack to some possibility\nthat Eisenhower might still go to\nthe NATO council meeting in\nParis Dpc. 16.\nHagerty laughed off a report\ner's request for comment on\ntwo London newspapers' sug\ngestions that Eisenhower would\nresign. \"Just say I laughed and\nsaid I haven't any reaction,\"\nHagerty replied.\nHagerty also was asked about a\nsuggestion by Sen. Bridges (R\nNH) that Nixon take over some\npresidential duties.\n\u201cI\u2019ve heard no discussion of\nthat by anyone and that includes\nthe vice president,\u201d Hagerty said.\nHagerty emphasized that the\nPresident and only the President\nwill decide who will represent the\nUnited States at the NATO sum\nmit conference, if it is held as\nscheduled.\nHe said there were no plans to\npostpone the meeting and the\nDec. 16 session is \u201can annual\nmeeting.\u201d","height":"18090","width":"13356"}}
